Introduction

Email Marketing remains one of the most effective ways to advertise on the Internet (Subramania and Bala (2018)). With over 3.8 billion email users worldwide and an expected 4.4 billion user increase in 2023, email has the broadest marketing reach (Harper (2022)). In addition to reaching so many people, it outperforms any other digital marketing strategy in terms of return on investment (ROI), customer preference, and the average cost per acquisition (CPA) (Harper (2022)). According to Subramania and Jeshurun, 81% of small to medium-sized businesses rely on email as their primary customer acquisition channel. One reason is that American online shoppers are more likely to shop as a result of what they read in an email (Subramania and Bala (2018)). Consumers like email rewards such as getting a special offer, a coupon they can redeem, or an online-exclusive price (Kimixay, Cheng, and Xiangdong (2019)). An empirical study on the effect of email marketing on consumers’ behavior discovered that the majority of consumers prefer brands that remember who they are, recognize their interests, and offer recommendations that are relevant to them personally (Kimixay, Cheng, and Xiangdong (2019)). However, it is vital not to over-personalize email content because it can annoy consumers (Kimixay, Cheng, and Xiangdong (2019)).

Regarding acquisition cost, emails have the lowest average acquisition (CPA) cost of around $10, compared to social media – $20, direct mail – $31, paid search – $16, and online display ads – $25 (Wolfe (2017)). Acquisition cost is critical since most brands aim to reach as many people as possible. However, as the usage of email marketing is expanding, it is becoming increasingly difficult to launch a successful email campaign. According to Statista, over 3,692,130 legitimate emails were globally sent every second in 2021 and this number is projected to increase by 4.5% annually in the next five years(Statista (2021)). Therefore, businesses must have a well-designed database and a well-executed email marketing strategy to succeed.

The purpose of this paper is to evaluate the integrity and accuracy of the email list of a Fintech startup. This is an important step in optimizing the performance of the company’s email marketing campaigns. Secondly, the paper prescribes action plans for running an effective email marketing campaign.

Descriptive Analysis

An accurate and high quality data includes characteristics such as:

Validity: The degree to which your data conforms to defined business rules or constraints.

Accuracy: Ensure your data is close to the true values.

Completeness: The degree to which all required data is known.

Consistency: Ensure your data is consistent within the same dataset and/or across multiple data sets.

Uniformity: The degree to which the data is specified using the same unit of measure.

Data Manipulation and Transformation

Inconsistent Attributes’ Name

The data include inconsistent attribute names across different datasets. This inconsistency needs to be corrected in order to merge all six datasets. To eliminate attributes’ name inconsistency, we introduce a naming convention and rename all the attributes accross all datasets to match the convention. The code snippet below, depicts a sample renaming that was done for all the datasets to introduce data consitency.

# Reformatting all 6 datasets to have matching attribute names. 
# Naming Convention: username, full_name, email, phone
#Sample reformatted dataset
cypetter_3rd <- cypetter_3rd %>%
  rename(phone = "Public Phone") %>%
  rename(email = "Public Email") %>%
  rename(full_name = "Full Name") %>%
  rename(username = "User Name")

Duplicated Values

The datasets include duplicated email addresses. Duplicated email addresses violate data validity and accuracy; therefore, all duplications need to be identified and corrected. The table below shows the number of duplicated email addresses in each dataset. To correct email duplications, we remove all duplicated email addresses.

Since there are no missing email addresses across all datasets and the unit of measurement in all attributes are the same, the dataset represents uniformity and completeness. Since our dataset now passes all the characteristics of a high quality data, we are ready to move on.

Email Correctness Algorithm

Here, we build an algorithm to verify the correctness of each email address based on their attributes. Note that there is no point in trying to work out if an email address is ‘valid’. A user is far more likely to enter a wrong, yet valid email address than they are to enter an invalid one. Any mistype will defenitely result in an incorrect email address but only maybe result in an invalid email address (Gilbertson (2019)). Therefore, the algorithm below identifies the probability of an incorrect email address.

# Checking for duplicate emails.
cypetter_1st<- cypetter_1st %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)
cypetter_2nd<- cypetter_2nd %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)
cypetter_3rd<- cypetter_3rd %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)
cypetter_4th<- cypetter_4th %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)
cypetter_5th<- cypetter_5th %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)
cypetter_6th<- cypetter_6th %>%
  filter(duplicated(email) == FALSE)

First, we create a function to split the fullnames by spaces. The splitted strings will then be stored in a list. We also create another attribute that keeps track of the number of strings in the list of splitted strings. The algorithm that splits the names is shown below and the table shows the results after running the algorithm.

# Splitting fullname by spaces into a list 
nameSplit <- function (dataset) {
  # Changing attributes to lowercase
  dataset$full_name<- str_to_lower(dataset$full_name)
  dataset$email<- str_to_lower(dataset$email)
  dataset$username<- str_to_lower(dataset$username)
  # Splitting fullname by spaces into a list
  dataset$splitted_fullname_list <- strsplit(dataset$full_name, split=" ")
  # A new attribute that counts the number of characters in the list of splitted names.
  dataset$num_chars <- 
    ifelse(!is.na(dataset$splitted_fullname_list), lengths(dataset$splitted_fullname_list), 0)
  return(dataset)
}

Our next algorithm computes a weighted email correctness confidence score between 0 and 100, with 0 being entirely incorrect and 100 being entirely correct. This algorithm takes the attributes, such as full name, username, relevant words in the email, and phone number into account. It calculates a weighted score for each email based on the attributes’ importance. The weighted score is calculated using the following five steps:

  1. If the email address contains the entire full name, then assign 1/1 confidence or 100% confidence that the email is correct. Example: full name: “Parsa Keyvani” email:parsakeyvani1@gmail.com

  2. If an email address does not contain the entire full name (example: full name: “Parsa Keyvani” and email: keyvanip@union.edu), then assign a weighted score based on how many words in the fullname are in the email address. The weighted score is calculated using the formula below: 1-(num_words_match / num_words). Example: full name: “Parsa Keyvani” splitting this into two strings and converting to lowercase we get “parsa” and “keyvani”, we see that only “keyvani” is in the email address keyvanip@union.edu. So the score that will be assigned to this case is (½ of 50%) and the remaining score that is left to give is 1-½ = ½ or 50%

  3. If the username is entirely in the email address, then assign the rest of the points to be 1/1 or 100%. Example: Using the example in part 2, the remaining score that this email address can get is 1/2 or 50%. Suppose the username of the person was keyvanip. Since the entire username is contained in the email, we give the rest of the points so (1-½ =½ points are added to the original points). So ½+½ =1 or 100% confidence that the email address is correct.

  4. If an email contains words relevant to a pet owner, like “pet”, “dog”, “cat”, “paw”, then we assume that the email is relevant and, therefore, we allocate some points. Example: email: justalittleredpets@gmail.com. Suppose the algorithm has given 2/3 or 66% score from the previous constraints. Since the email address contains a relevant word, “pet”, we assign a weighted point and add to the current score. The weighted point is calculated here (1-⅔)/2 so the person gets 0.15 points added to their total points (0.15+ 0.66=0.81 or 81% confidence.

  5. If it contains a phone number, we add points as well, but only if they have already gained points from previous constraints. In other words, if an email address has yet to get any points, even if they have a phone number, it will gain no points. Consider the example in constraint 4. So far, this person has received 0.81 points, now we check to see if the person has a phone number, and since they do, we add extra points: 1-(0.81)/2= 0.095 points get added, so their total score is 0.91 or 91% confidence that the email address is correct.

emailValidityScore <- function (dataset) {
  # Generates string match attribute that is a number indicating how many strings match.
  i<-1  
  while (i<=nrow(dataset)){
    if (!dataset$num_chars[i]==0){
      dataset$string_match[i] <- sum(stri_detect_fixed(dataset$email[i], unlist(dataset$splitted_fullname_list[i])) == TRUE)}
    else {dataset$string_match[i] <- 0
    }
    i=i+1
  }
  # assign full score to a person if all the fullname is inside the email address.
  dataset$points <- dataset$string_match/dataset$num_chars
  dataset$points <- ifelse(is.na(dataset$points), 0, dataset$points)
  dataset$constraintsMet <- ifelse(dataset$points==0,0,1)
    
  # Validity check for the rest of the constraints
  i<-1  
  remaining <-0
  while (i<=nrow(dataset)){
    # if fullname is not entirely in the email address, run below statement.
    if (dataset$points[i] !=1){
      remaining <- 1-dataset$points[i] 
      # does email match with username?
      if (stri_detect_fixed(dataset$email[i], dataset$username[i]) ==TRUE){
        dataset$points[i] <- remaining +dataset$points[i]
        remaining <- 1-dataset$points[i] 
        dataset$constraintsMet[i] <- 2
      }
      # Does email contain relevant words?
      else if (str_detect(dataset$email[i], "pet") || str_detect(dataset$email[i], "dog") ||
               str_detect(dataset$email[i], "cat") || str_detect(dataset$email[i], "paw")){ 
        dataset$points[i] <- remaining/2 +dataset$points[i]
        remaining <- 1-dataset$points[i]
        dataset$constraintsMet[i] <- 3
        # Does the entity also have a phone number?
        if (!is.na(dataset$phone[i])){
          dataset$points[i]<- remaining/2 +dataset$points[i]
          dataset$constraintsMet[i] <- 4}
      }
      # Does the entity have a phone number?
      else if (!is.na(dataset$phone[i]) && dataset$points[i]!=0){
        dataset$points[i] <- remaining/3 +dataset$points[i]
        dataset$constraintsMet[i] <- 4
      }
      i=i+1
      remaining <-0
    }
    else {
      dataset$constraintsMet[i] <- 1
      i=i+1
    }
  }
  dataset$points <- round(dataset$points, 2)
  return(dataset)
}

Data Visulaization & Insights

Diagnostic Analysis

The insights from running the algorithm on the datasets indicate that most emails fell into the first constraint: their splitted full name matched their email address. However, what is shocking and rather alarming is that around 25% of emails did not meet any of the five algorithm constraints. Even though the algorithm did not find any similarities between the email address and other attributes, it is still very much possible for the email to be a correct and valid email address.

Additionally, the algorithm could, at most, have five constraints with the available attributes. This is one of our limitationsin this project. With more attributes, the algorithm’s accuracy can be significantly improved and the false negatives can also be reduced.

Below are a few emails the algorithm declared incorrect because it did not pass any constraints.

In the table above, we can see a few false negative instances. For example, in the first and fourth entities, based on splitted_fullname_list and username, we can see that the emails have a good chance of being correct; however, the algorithm did not detect any similarities present. This is because the algorithm needs to be more intelligent to compare similarities between names and email addresses. In the first entity, the algorithm takes the full name and compares it to the email because space does not exist to separate the full name. Because the splitted full name does not entirely match that of the email, it returns false and does not pass the first constraint. Similarly, the entire username is not in the email, so it declares false even though the human eye sees some similarities. In the fourth entity, the email includes ‘pt’ as its abbreviation for ‘physical therapy.’ However, because the algorithm is not intelligent enough, it cannot detect word abbreviations that a human can detect, so the algorithm returns false.

The current algorithm is not very accurate, and there is no way for it to be as accurate as a human because no matter how many constraints we add, the algorithm will not be as intelligent as a human. As mentioned in the above paragraph, the algorithm cannot correctly identify all the possibilities because some instances are apparent to humans but are not obvious or cannot be made evident to an algorithm. Therefore, the best practice is using this algorithm on large datasets to identify all the emails in which the algorithm has 100% confidence. For those instances that the algorithm believes to be false, we can use human labor to check for any false negatives. This is the most efficient and accurate way of approaching the problem because we have drastically narrowed the problem.

Prescriptive Analysis

Previous literature on email marketing and customer behavior suggests that email marketing is increasingly recognized as an effective internet marketing tool (GhavamiLahiji and Abbas (2016)). Tests and studies reveal that email marketing can affect consumer behavior, even convincing consumers to go to websites for more information or to make a purchase (Pulevska Ivanovska and Karadakoska (2015)).

Many literature reviews have been conducted that study the success factors of email marketing. For example, an email marketing study claimed that studying customers’ email open and purchase behaviors is necessary because studying only one can be misleading. Their empirical study shows that some very active email openers are the least active in their purchase behaviors. In addition, some email-inactive customers are relatively active in their purchase behaviors (Zhang, Kumar, and Cosguner (2017)). Thus, if firms focus solely on the email open rate to allocate their resources, they might overlook a pool of customers who are inactive in responding to emails but are relatively active in purchases.

Another study emphasized the importance of personalized email marketing. Consumers are overloaded with information, both wanted and unwanted. In fact, spam accounts for 88% of all email traffic. Adding consumer-specific information (e.g., recipient’s name) can be beneficial for consumers to open marketing emails and not mark them spam. The study ran an experiment and found that adding the name of the message recipient to the email’s subject line increased the probability of the recipient opening it by 20%, which translated to an increase in sales leads by 31% and a reduction in the number of individuals unsubscribing from the email campaign by 17% (Pavlov, Melville, and Plice (2008)). This indicates that email personalization can lead to acquiring more customers and retaining previous customers.

In addition to personalized marketing, some studies found permission email marketing (PEM) to positively influence online shopping behavior (Sahni, Wheeler, and Chintagunta (2018)). The results of the studies indicate that PEM affects the perceived usefulness, ease of use, and enjoyment derived from shopping online. It also serves to reduce the perceived risk (Mogos and Acatrinei (2015)).

A model designed by a study on the success factors of email marketing suggests that there are three stages in effective email marketing (Rettie (2017)):

  • getting the recipient to open the email
  • getting them to pay attention to the email
  • persuading them to click through the URL link

Hence, the response rate should depend on the email header in the inbox, the email contents, and the recipient.

The same study researched 30 email marketing campaigns and found factors, such as subject line, email length, incentive, and the number of images, to be associated with increased response rate. Additionally, the study conducted a regression analysis in which they discovered the following correlations.

  • Higher response rates correlate with more attractive email subject lines.
  • Higher response rates correlate with more attractive incentives.
  • Response rate is inversely related to the email length.
  • Higher response rates correlate with more images.
  • Higher response rates correlate with emails from well-known brands.
  • Permission email has higher response rates.
  • Response rates are higher for respondents who receive fewer emails.
  • Response rate is higher for HTML than text messages.
  • Respondents who have used the Internet for longer are more likely to respond.
  • Elderly consumers do not prefer email marketing methods for daily purchases. Whereas, younger consumers prefer using email marketing methods for daily purchases.
  • Female consumers prefer using “Email marketing” methods for daily purchases.
  • Consumers with higher education prefer to use “Email marketing.”
  • People with lower education levels tend to prefer “Email marketing” less for their daily purchases than those with a higher education levels.
  • Higher responses were recorded for respondents who had bought online, aged 30 -34, or with incomes over £35,000.

In conclusion, if the Fintech startup implements some of the suggestions mentioned in this section, they can significantly improve their email marketing strategy leading to higher customer acquisition and retention.
